<section class="xm-glossary-section">
  <details class="xm-glossary-details">
    <summary class="xm-glossary-summary">Glossary — Key Terms<span class="xm-chevron">+</span></summary>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Samhain</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">(pronounced "sow-in") The Celtic festival of the dead, observed October 31 to November 1, marking the Celtic new year and the night the spirit-veil between living and dead was believed to be thinnest. The direct ancestor of modern Halloween.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Cross-quarter day</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">A day falling at the midpoint between a solstice and an equinox, marking a high day in the pagan solar calendar. The four cross-quarter days are Imbolc (Feb 1), Beltane (May 1), Lughnasadh (Aug 1), and Samhain (Oct 31).</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Wheel of the Year</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">The eight-festival pagan calendar of modern Wicca and Neopaganism — the four solstices and equinoxes plus the four cross-quarter days. Samhain is one of its high holy days.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">All Hallows' Eve / All Saints' Day / All Souls' Day</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">The three-day Catholic cluster (Oct 31, Nov 1, Nov 2) layered over the Celtic Samhain by Popes Gregory III (731–741 AD), Gregory IV (~837 AD), and Odilo of Cluny (998 AD). The Christianized envelope around the pre-existing festival of the dead.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Guising</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">The Celtic-Scottish practice of donning spirit-of-the-dead costumes and going door to door at Samhain, performing songs or recitations in exchange for food. The direct ancestor of modern trick-or-treating.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Souling</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">The medieval Catholic practice of going door to door on All Hallows' Eve requesting "soul cakes" in exchange for prayers for the household's dead. The Catholic-frame version of guising; the secondary direct ancestor of trick-or-treating.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Familiar spirit (Hebrew: 'ōb, אוֹב, H178)</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">A wandering or attendant spirit, sometimes localized in an animal or object, consulted for divination or aid. Yahuah's prohibition of familiar spirits is explicit in Leviticus 19:31, 20:6, 20:27, and Devarim 18:11. The Halloween black cat and witch's familiar belong to this category.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Witch (Hebrew: m'khashēphāh, מְכַשֵּׁפָה, H3784)</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">A practitioner of sorcery and enchantment. Yahuah's command in Exodus 22:18 is the strongest prohibition of any practice in Torah. The Halloween witch is the cartoon survival of a real religious category Yahuah named for destruction.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Pharmakeia (Greek: φαρμακεία)</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">The New Testament Greek word for sorcery, witchcraft, and the use of magical drugs and potions. Listed among the works of the flesh in Galatians 5:20. The root of modern English "pharmacy."</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Necromancy</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">The practice of consulting the dead for knowledge or counsel. Forbidden by Devarim 18:11. The Halloween séance, Ouija board, ghost-hunting experience, and haunted house all sit in this category.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Trunk or Treat</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">The modern American evangelical church's Christianized version of trick-or-treating, held in church parking lots. A "safe alternative" framing that retains the festival's date, costumes, and practice while changing only the location and the candy supplier.</span>
    </div>

    <div class="xm-gloss-entry">
      <span class="xm-gloss-term">Pomona</span>
      <span class="xm-gloss-def">Roman goddess of fruit trees and orchards, whose autumn festival was absorbed into the British Samhain after the Roman conquest. The apple-bobbing divination descends from her cult.</span>
    </div>
  </details>
</section>

